  "texts": [
    "When someone explains to us that something we did was wrong, she does not merely tell us that the act was wrong, but also suggests the particular way in which the act was wrong, e.g.",
    "by drawing on familiar examples, by prompting our imagination ('How would you feel if something like this happened to you?",
    "'), or by using a certain tone of voice.",
    "We understand these cues because we are accustomed to a 'whirl of organism' in which they have a place.",
    "How is this Wittgensteinian picture of moral training relevant to our confidence -or lack thereof -that another agent, or system, has moral competence?"
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}